If you want to **build an internal leak-detection framework inside your C++ program** (using something like a **Tester singleton**) and automatically detect leaks across **inheritance, polymorphism, and edge-case scenarios**, the idea is to implement **instrumented allocation tracking + automated test scenarios**.

This approach is commonly used in **game engines and large C++ frameworks**.

I'll show a clean architecture.

---

# 1. Core idea

You instrument memory allocation so that **every allocation is registered**, then your **Tester singleton validates that allocations return to zero after each scenario**.

Workflow:

```
Test case start
    ↓
snapshot allocation state
    ↓
run edge case scenario
    ↓
compare allocations
    ↓
report leaks
```

---

# 2. Global allocation tracker

Override `new` / `delete` to track all allocations.

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>
#include <mutex>

class MemoryTracker {
public:
    static MemoryTracker& instance() {
        static MemoryTracker tracker;
        return tracker;
    }

    void add(void* ptr, size_t size) {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mutex);
        allocations[ptr] = size;
    }

    void remove(void* ptr) {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(mutex);
        allocations.erase(ptr);
    }

    size_t allocationCount() const {
        return allocations.size();
    }

private:
    std::unordered_map<void*, size_t> allocations;
    std::mutex mutex;
};
```

---

# 3. Hook global new/delete

```cpp
void* operator new(size_t size) {
    void* ptr = malloc(size);
    MemoryTracker::instance().add(ptr, size);
    return ptr;
}

void operator delete(void* ptr) noexcept {
    MemoryTracker::instance().remove(ptr);
    free(ptr);
}
```

Now **every object allocation in your program is tracked**, including:

* base classes
* derived classes
* polymorphic allocations
* STL containers

---

# 4. Tester Singleton

Your tester runs **scenarios and validates leaks automatically**.

```cpp
class Tester {
public:
    static Tester& instance() {
        static Tester t;
        return t;
    }

    void runTest(std::function<void()> scenario, const std::string& name) {

        auto before = MemoryTracker::instance().allocationCount();

        scenario();

        auto after = MemoryTracker::instance().allocationCount();

        if (before != after)
        {
            std::cout << "Leak detected in test: " << name << "\n";
            std::cout << "Alloc diff: " << after - before << "\n";
        }
        else
        {
            std::cout << "Test passed: " << name << "\n";
        }
    }
};
```

---

# 5. Edge-case scenario tests

Now you write **scenarios specifically designed to stress polymorphism and inheritance**.

Example:

```cpp
Tester::instance().runTest([](){

    Base* obj = new Derived();
    delete obj;

}, "virtual destructor test");
```

If `Base` destructor is not virtual → leak detected.

---

# 6. Stress tests for polymorphism

Example scenario:

```cpp
Tester::instance().runTest([](){

    std::vector<Base*> objects;

    for(int i=0;i<10000;i++)
        objects.push_back(new Derived());

    for(auto o : objects)
        delete o;

}, "mass polymorphic allocation");
```

This reveals leaks caused by:

* incorrect destructors
* missing deletes
* container ownership mistakes

---

# 7. Exception edge cases

Memory leaks often happen in **exception paths**.

```cpp
Tester::instance().runTest([](){

    try {
        Base* ptr = new Derived();
        throw std::runtime_error("fail");
        delete ptr;
    }
    catch(...) {}

}, "exception path leak");
```

---

# 8. Factory / ownership edge case

```cpp
Tester::instance().runTest([](){

    auto factory = []() -> Base* {
        return new Derived();
    };

    Base* obj = factory();
    delete obj;

}, "factory ownership");
```

---

# 9. Detect leaks by type (advanced)

You can also record **typeid**:

```cpp
#include <typeindex>

struct AllocationInfo
{
    size_t size;
    std::type_index type;
};
```

Then track:

```
Derived : 12 leaked objects
Texture : 4 leaked objects
```

This helps when polymorphism hides the real type.

---

# 10. Snapshot-based leak detection

Better method:

```
snapshot A
run scenario
snapshot B
diff
```

Example:

```cpp
size_t snapshot() {
    return MemoryTracker::instance().allocationCount();
}
```

---

# 11. Automatic scenario generation (powerful)

You can also generate tests like:

```
N allocations
random deletes
container insert/remove
exception interrupts
```

Example fuzz-like test:

```cpp
Tester::instance().runTest([](){

    std::vector<Base*> objs;

    for(int i=0;i<1000;i++)
    {
        objs.push_back(new Derived());

        if(rand()%3)
        {
            delete objs.back();
            objs.pop_back();
        }
    }

    for(auto o : objs)
        delete o;

}, "random ownership stress");
```

This catches **non-obvious lifetime bugs**.

---

# 12. Detect leaks at program shutdown

Add in `main`:

```cpp
if(MemoryTracker::instance().allocationCount() != 0)
    std::cout << "Program ended with leaks\n";
```

---

# 13. Optional: callstack capture

You can record **where allocations happen** using:

* `backtrace()` (Linux)
* `CaptureStackBackTrace()` (Windows)

Then the tester prints the **exact allocation site**.

---

# Final architecture

```
MemoryTracker
      ↑
global new/delete
      ↑
Tester Singleton
      ↑
Scenario tests
      ↑
Edge-case generators
```

This gives you **fully automated internal leak detection without Valgrind**.

